00:00:53,187 --> 00:00:55,253
narrator: they may have stopped making the car.         

4
00:00:55,255 --> 00:00:57,857
but they still manufacture replacement gauges        

5
00:00:57,859 --> 00:01:00,259
that look just like the originals.       

6
00:01:00,261 --> 00:01:02,661
after all, modern digital instruments    

7
00:01:02,663 --> 00:01:03,796
just wouldn't look right     

8
00:01:03,798 --> 00:01:06,632
in the dashboard of a classic vehicle.      

9
00:01:06,634 --> 00:01:09,135
technicians give the mechanism a bit of an update,       

10
00:01:09,137 --> 00:01:11,203
but the look is all retro.    

11
00:01:13,841 --> 00:01:15,674
these car gauges are new.    

12
00:01:15,676 --> 00:01:17,677
but they have the same old faces.       

13
00:01:17,679 --> 00:01:21,813
the old-style dials are built to the original designs     

14
00:01:21,815 --> 00:01:26,218
as replacement parts for classic and vintage vehicles.  

15
00:01:26,220 --> 00:01:27,953
making a classic car gauge    

16
00:01:27,955 --> 00:01:31,490
starts with a zinc-coated steel blank.    

17
00:01:31,492 --> 00:01:34,092
a worker places the blank on a tool.       

18
00:01:34,094 --> 00:01:36,295
a press stretches it around the form         

19
00:01:36,297 --> 00:01:38,430
to shape it into the gauge case.              

20
00:01:38,432 --> 00:01:41,167
after a flange has been formed on the rim    

21
00:01:41,169 --> 00:01:43,769
and holes punched for assembly purposes,      

22
00:01:43,771 --> 00:01:46,171
it's on to the next operation.  

23
00:01:46,173 --> 00:01:49,241
a worker welds a stud to the back of the case.     

24
00:01:49,243 --> 00:01:54,046
the stud will be used to mount the gauge to the dashboard.   

25
00:01:54,048 --> 00:01:57,283
another worker paints the inside of the case white.  

26
00:02:00,054 --> 00:02:03,723
next up is a brass tube for the light bulb.       

27
00:02:03,725 --> 00:02:08,126
a worker secures it in a fixture and places the case over it.   

28
00:02:08,128 --> 00:02:10,262
a press crimps the top of the light tube    

29
00:02:10,264 --> 00:02:12,264
around one of the holes in the case,           

30
00:02:12,266 --> 00:02:16,268
securing the tube to the back.  

31
00:02:16,270 --> 00:02:17,803
a mechanized printer pad     

32
00:02:17,805 --> 00:02:20,472
picks up ink from engravings on a metal plate         

33
00:02:20,474 --> 00:02:22,708
and transfers them to a dial.  

34
00:02:27,081 --> 00:02:30,015
for this gauge, they'll need a hollow, curved spring,     

35
00:02:30,017 --> 00:02:32,951
known as a bourdon tube.     

36
00:02:32,953 --> 00:02:35,688
to shape this flat brass tube into a spring,          

37
00:02:35,690 --> 00:02:38,891
a worker tucks one end into a forming tool.       

38
00:02:38,893 --> 00:02:40,826
he inserts a shim into the other end        

39
00:02:40,828 --> 00:02:42,294
to keep the tube hollow     

40
00:02:42,296 --> 00:02:45,297
as he curls it around the form.         

41
00:02:45,299 --> 00:02:50,235
this turns the flat tube into a c-shape spring.      

42
00:02:50,237 --> 00:02:54,573
he then crimps one end in this press.          

43
00:02:54,575 --> 00:02:57,976
he dips the crimped end     
into a chemical cleaning agent  

44
00:02:57,978 --> 00:02:59,578
and then into hot solder.    

45
00:02:59,580 --> 00:03:01,513
the solder hardens        

46
00:03:01,515 --> 00:03:04,116
and seals this end of the bourdon spring.      

47
00:03:07,321 --> 00:03:09,054
he solders a brass adapter    

48
00:03:09,056 --> 00:03:11,657
to the opened end of the bourdon tube.       

49
00:03:11,659 --> 00:03:13,391
this hollow socket        

50
00:03:13,393 --> 00:03:15,994
is the part that will receive the fluid pressure.       

51
00:03:15,996 --> 00:03:19,198
that pressure will cause the tube to unwind        

52
00:03:19,200 --> 00:03:22,268
and move gears that turn    
the pointer on the gauge dial.  

53
00:03:26,274 --> 00:03:28,741
a worker places the tube in water        

54
00:03:28,743 --> 00:03:33,212
and pumps pressurized air into it through the socket.   

55
00:03:33,214 --> 00:03:36,082
he checks for bubbles that would indicate there's a leak.     

56
00:03:39,086 --> 00:03:41,319
they make the gears that move the pointer      

57
00:03:41,321 --> 00:03:43,622
using a hobbing machine.     

58
00:03:43,624 --> 00:03:45,958
it's a spinning cutter that carves teeth        

59
00:03:45,960 --> 00:03:50,162
into brass parts, known as racks.         

60
00:03:50,164 --> 00:03:54,834
a worker inserts a brass pivot in a holding device.       

61
00:03:54,836 --> 00:03:56,168
using a press,          

62
00:03:56,170 --> 00:03:58,571
she crimps the pivot to the center of the rack.    

63
00:04:02,509 --> 00:04:04,777
she then assembles a hair spring and a pinion    

64
00:04:04,779 --> 00:04:06,779
between two brass plates.    

65
00:04:10,384 --> 00:04:13,119
she positions the rack in the gear sandwich.      

66
00:04:16,190 --> 00:04:19,558
she secures the assembly using a hand press.       

67
00:04:22,463 --> 00:04:25,664
now, with tweezers, she pulls the end of the spring             

68
00:04:25,666 --> 00:04:27,466
through a hole in one of the posts       

69
00:04:27,468 --> 00:04:31,337
and locks it in place with a pin.           

70
00:04:31,339 --> 00:04:33,005
she turns the shaft to confirm  

71
00:04:33,007 --> 00:04:37,742
that the rack-and-pinion gears engage and work smoothly.    

72
00:04:37,744 --> 00:04:40,212
returning to the bourdon tubes,      

73
00:04:40,214 --> 00:04:42,281
she transfers one to a fixture  

74
00:04:42,283 --> 00:04:43,883
and locks it in place.      

75
00:04:47,421 --> 00:04:50,356
she places the gears on top of the bourdon tube    

76
00:04:50,358 --> 00:04:53,058
and screws it to the side of the socket.    

77
00:04:56,230 --> 00:04:58,363
she then installs the bourdon tube assembly    

78
00:04:58,365 --> 00:05:00,266
in the gas gauge casing.     

79
00:05:04,972 --> 00:05:06,906
a worker now connects the gauge              

80
00:05:06,908 --> 00:05:10,376
to a pressurized air source.   

81
00:05:10,378 --> 00:05:13,111
she pops the retro-look dial into the device         

82
00:05:13,113 --> 00:05:16,581
and attaches the pointer to the protruding gear shaft.  

83
00:05:16,583 --> 00:05:19,051
she then introduces air at a known pressure       

84
00:05:19,053 --> 00:05:20,753
to calibrate the gauge.     

85
00:05:24,258 --> 00:05:28,928
she tucks a gasket into the top rim         

86
00:05:28,930 --> 00:05:31,530
and then fits a glass pane on top.       

87
00:05:35,202 --> 00:05:38,737
a chrome-plated bezel retains the assembly and frames it.   

88
00:05:41,275 --> 00:05:43,876
a press snaps the components together.     

89
00:05:47,415 --> 00:05:52,217
made to measure, this car gauge is now complete,            

90
00:05:52,219 --> 00:05:54,486
and it looks like a classic.   

